notesStmt.note: This is an illuminated and illustrated copy of the famous story of Joseph and the Potiphar's wife (Yūsuf va Zulaykhā) by Jāmī (d. 898 AH / 1492 CE). The manuscript was written in India in the late twelfth century AH / eighteenth CE in black nastaʿlīq script. There are forty-seven paintings illustrating the text. The lacquer binding with floral decoration is attributable to the thirteenth century AH / nineteenth CE.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Persian.

layoutDesc.layout: Two columns; double frame for the text and the marginalia

handDesc.handNote: Written in black Indian nastaʿlīq script with section headings in red

decoDesc.decoNote: Forty-seven illustrations; double-page illuminated incipit with headpiece inscribed with the doxological formula (basmalah), cloud-bands, and a border

binding.p: Possibly dates to the thirteenth century AH / nineteenth CE; lacquer (no flap); floral design covering the whole surface of the boards, including the central ovals and pendants
